info","should_display_ad_info":false},"serialized_frtp_identifiers":null,"debug_info":null,"inform_treatment_for_community_notes":null,"message":{"text":"\u2705 Treasure Tuesday\nPasquier Bronze Seal Found - September 2011 \n\nExcerpts from an article by James Sinclair\nIn September 2011 Captain Andy Matroci and the crew of the J.B. Magruder were continuing to develop an area on the northern end of the Northwest artifact scatter trail of the Nuestra Senora de Atocha, 1622 when they found this bronze seal.\n\nBronze seals such as these were used by nobility, church and government functionaries for impressing designs onto official papers. Hot \u201csealing wax\u201d would be applied to the document then the seal would be used to impress the image into the wax. It was, much as today, a way of ensuring the authenticity of the document.\n\nThe seal is obviously an image of an heraldic coat of arms, usually associated with a noble family. We contacted various experts in the Heraldry of that period and we were thrilled with the news that came back. The Coat of Arms belonged to Don Pedro Pasquier de Esparza, Almirante of the 1622 Tierra Firma Fleet.\n\nThe name Pasquier is of French origin, Don Pedro comes from a very old and noble family of Tudela, (Navarra). One needs to keep in mind that boarders and allegiances were a changeable situation then as they are now. We know that the family was living there since the middle Ages.  In the middle of the XVI century there were several Pasquier\u2019s in Navarra and almost surely they were his relatives. In 1617, Don Pedro Pasquier de Esparza received the title of Caballero de la Orden de Calatrava, an order of military knighthood where they mentioned his grandfather\u2019s names. By 1621, the King most likely made a Royal Decree appointing him as the \u201cAlmirante\u201d of the Tierra Firme Fleet of 1622. In September of that year, Don Pedro and the other 264 people on board the Atocha sailed to their fate. Nearly 400 years later we have been able to research the various complexities of Spanish heraldry and we have switched the image and added the correct colors to fully appreciate the Coat of Arms of at Mel Fisher\u2019s Treasure Museum in Sebastian, FL! \ud83c\udf1f\n\nArtifact Tag Number: 68045\nDescription: Ornate Olive Blossom Chain\nLength: 0.5 inches\nGram Weight: 0.4 grams\nWreck: Corrigan\u2019s - 1715 Fleet\n\nOlive Blossom Chains are renowned for their intricate, hand-crafted design and high-karat gold composition, making them highly sought-after treasures. Each link was meticulously handcrafted and fused, showcasing the artistry of the era. Named by the Smithsonian Institution, these chains are a hallmark of historical significance. While individual pieces are occasionally recovered, intact segments like this are exceptionally rare!\n\nIn 1962, Real Eight member Rex Stocker made history by discovering an 11-foot Olive Blossom Chain on a beach, complete with a solid gold \u201cDragon Whistle,\u201d believed to be a Captain-General\u2019s badge of office.
